    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bowl-shaped basketry pot-lids made and used by the Zulu and other southern African peoples, traditionally fabricated of grasses, or, in recent times, of colored telephone wire. They are also sometimes used as dishes to hold small items or dry foodstuffs.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000048377/Kennedy, Art, Architecture and Material Culture of the Zulu Kingdom (1994)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Schaalvormige gevlochten potdeksels, vervaardigd en gebruikt door de Zoeloes en andere volkeren in zuidelijk Afrika, traditioneel gemaakt van gras of meer recentelijk van gekleurde telefoonkabels. Soms ook gebruikt als schalen waarop kleine dingen of droog voedsel kan worden gelegd.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
